I. Motivation

Bayesian analysis is predicated on the idea that we learn about unobserved quantities from quantities we are able to observe. All observed quantities (i.e. parameters, latent states, missing data, and even the data themselves before they are observed) are treated as random variables in the Bayesian approach. All Bayesian analysis extends from the laws of probability, that is, from the “mathematics of random variables.”

Random variables are quantities whose value is determined by chance. Statistical distributions represent how “chance” works by specifying the probability that a random variable takes on a value (in the discrete case) or falls within a range of values (in the continuous case). The goal of Bayesian analysis is to discover the characteristics of probability distributions that govern the behavior of random variables of interest, for example, the size of a population, the rate of nitrogen accumulation in a stream, the diversity of plants on a landscape, the change in lifetime income that occurs with changing level of education, the stress levels of juvenile elephants, the political party that will win a congressional district, etc.

It follows that, understanding the laws of probability and statistical distributions provides the foundation for Bayesian analysis. In this lab, we will focus on the following

  • Understanding the functional form of some of the primary deterministic models used in Bayesian modeling.
  • Understanding how to apply those models to different scientific questions.
  • Understand the concepts of conditional and independent random variables.
  • Be able to write out joint distributions of random variables given Bayesian networks (directed acyclic graphs).

Next week we will build upon this learning by exploring the ins and outs of different statistical distributions.

III. The chain rule of probability

1. Use the chain rule of probability to factor the joint distribution Pr(𝜃1,𝜃2,𝜃3,𝜃4)Pr(θ1,θ2,θ3,θ4) into a joint conditional distribution.

Pr(𝜃1,𝜃2,𝜃3,𝜃4)=×Pr(𝜃1∣𝜃2,𝜃3,𝜃4)×Pr(𝜃2∣𝜃3,𝜃4)×Pr(𝜃3∣𝜃4)×Pr(𝜃4)Pr(θ1,θ2,θ3,θ4)=×Pr(θ1∣θ2,θ3,θ4)×Pr(θ2∣θ3,θ4)×Pr(θ3∣θ4)×Pr(θ4)

The order doesn’t matter. The following is also correct:

Pr(𝜃1,𝜃2,𝜃3,𝜃4)=×Pr(𝜃4∣𝜃2,𝜃3,𝜃1)×Pr(𝜃2∣𝜃3,𝜃1)×Pr(𝜃3∣𝜃1)×Pr(𝜃1)Pr(θ1,θ2,θ3,θ4)=×Pr(θ4∣θ2,θ3,θ1)×Pr(θ2∣θ3,θ1)×Pr(θ3∣θ1)×Pr(θ1)

as are many other variations.


2. Consider the following factored joint distribution:

Pr(𝜃,𝑤,𝜂,𝛼)=Pr(𝛼∣𝑤,𝜂,𝜃)Pr(𝑤∣𝜂,𝜃)Pr(𝜂∣𝜃)Pr(𝜃)Pr(θ,w,η,α)=Pr(α∣w,η,θ)Pr(w∣η,θ)Pr(η∣θ)Pr(θ)
Simplify this equation using the knowledge that 𝜂η and 𝜃θ are independent and that 𝑤w and 𝜃θ are independent.

Pr(𝜃,𝑤,𝜂,𝛼)=Pr(𝛼∣𝑤,𝜂,𝜃)Pr(𝑤∣𝜂)Pr(𝜂)Pr(𝜃)Pr(θ,w,η,α)=Pr(α∣w,η,θ)Pr(w∣η)Pr(η)Pr(θ)


IV. Converting DAGs to joint distributions

Write out the joint and conditional distributions for the following Bayesian networks. For discrete random variables, [𝐴][A] is equivalent to Pr(𝐴)Pr(A). For continuous random variables [𝐴][A] is the probability density of 𝐴A.



1.Pr(𝑎,𝑏,𝑐,𝑑,𝑒)=Pr(𝑎∣𝑏,𝑐)Pr(𝑏∣𝑑,𝑒)Pr(𝑐)Pr(𝑑)Pr(𝑒)2.Pr(𝑦,𝑧,𝛽1,𝛽2,𝜃𝑝,𝜃𝑑)=Pr(𝑦∣𝑧,𝜃𝑑)Pr(𝑧∣𝜃𝑝)Pr(𝜃𝑑∣𝛽1,𝛽2)Pr(𝜃𝑝)Pr(𝛽1)Pr(𝛽2)3.Pr(𝑦,𝑥,𝜇,𝜙1,𝜙2,𝜎,𝑧)=Pr(𝑦∣𝑥,𝑧)Pr(𝑥∣𝜇,𝜎)Pr(𝑧∣𝜙1,𝜙2)Pr(𝜎)Pr(𝜙1)Pr(𝜙2)Pr(𝜇)4.Pr(𝑦1,𝑦2,𝑧,𝜃1,𝜃2,𝛾1,𝛾2,𝛾3)=Pr(𝑦1∣𝜃1,𝑧)Pr(𝑦2∣𝜃2,𝑧)Pr(𝑧∣𝛾1,𝛾2,𝛾3)Pr(𝜃1)Pr(𝜃2)Pr(𝛾1)Pr(𝛾2)Pr(𝛾3)5.Pr(𝐴,𝐵,𝐷,𝐸,𝐹,𝐻)=Pr(𝐴∣𝐷,𝐸)Pr(𝐷∣𝐻)Pr(𝐵∣𝐻,𝐹)Pr(𝐸)Pr(𝐻)Pr(𝐹)1.Pr(a,b,c,d,e)=Pr(a∣b,c)Pr(b∣d,e)Pr(c)Pr(d)Pr(e)2.Pr(y,z,β1,β2,θp,θd)=Pr(y∣z,θd)Pr(z∣θp)Pr(θd∣β1,β2)Pr(θp)Pr(β1)Pr(β2)3.Pr(y,x,μ,ϕ1,ϕ2,σ,z)=Pr(y∣x,z)Pr(x∣μ,σ)Pr(z∣ϕ1,ϕ2)Pr(σ)Pr(ϕ1)Pr(ϕ2)Pr(μ)4.Pr(y1,y2,z,θ1,θ2,γ1,γ2,γ3)=Pr(y1∣θ1,z)Pr(y2∣θ2,z)Pr(z∣γ1,γ2,γ3)Pr(θ1)Pr(θ2)Pr(γ1)Pr(γ2)Pr(γ3)5.Pr(A,B,D,E,F,H)=Pr(A∣D,E)Pr(D∣H)Pr(B∣H,F)Pr(E)Pr(H)Pr(F)


V. Converting joint distributions to DAGs

Draw Bayesian networks (DAGs) for the joint and conditional distributions below.

I.Pr(𝐴,𝐵)=Pr(𝐴∣𝐵)Pr(𝐵)II.Pr(𝐴,𝐵,𝐶)=Pr(𝐴∣𝐵,𝐶)Pr(𝐵∣𝐶)Pr(𝐶)III.Pr(𝐴,𝐵,𝐶,𝐷)=Pr(𝐴∣𝐶)Pr(𝐵∣𝐶)Pr(𝐶∣𝐷)Pr(𝐷)IV.Pr(𝐴,𝐵,𝐶,𝐷,𝐸)=Pr(𝐴∣𝐶)Pr(𝐵∣𝐶)Pr(𝐶∣𝐷,𝐸)Pr(𝐷)Pr(𝐸)V.Pr(𝐴,𝐵,𝐶,𝐷)=Pr(𝐴∣𝐵,𝐶,𝐷)Pr(𝐵∣𝐶,𝐷)Pr(𝐶∣𝐷)Pr(𝐷)VI.Pr(𝐴,𝐵,𝐶,𝐷)=Pr(𝐴∣𝐵,𝐶,𝐷)Pr(𝐶∣𝐷)Pr(𝐵)Pr(𝐷)I.Pr(A,B)=Pr(A∣B)Pr(B)II.Pr(A,B,C)=Pr(A∣B,C)Pr(B∣C)Pr(C)III.Pr(A,B,C,D)=Pr(A∣C)Pr(B∣C)Pr(C∣D)Pr(D)IV.Pr(A,B,C,D,E)=Pr(A∣C)Pr(B∣C)Pr(C∣D,E)Pr(D)Pr(E)V.Pr(A,B,C,D)=Pr(A∣B,C,D)Pr(B∣C,D)Pr(C∣D)Pr(D)VI.Pr(A,B,C,D)=Pr(A∣B,C,D)Pr(C∣D)Pr(B)Pr(D)



VI. Simplifying

Simplify the expression below, given that 𝑧2z2 and 𝑧3z3 are independent random variables.

Pr(𝑧1,𝑧2,𝑧3)=Pr(𝑧1∣𝑧2,𝑧3)Pr(𝑧2∣𝑧3)Pr(𝑧3)Pr(z1,z2,z3)=Pr(z1∣z2,z3)Pr(z2∣z3)Pr(z3)

The expression simplifies to

Pr(𝑧1,𝑧2,𝑧3)=Pr(𝑧1∣𝑧2,𝑧3)Pr(𝑧2)Pr(𝑧3)Pr(z1,z2,z3)=Pr(z1∣z2,z3)Pr(z2)Pr(z3)
because Pr(𝑧2∣𝑧3)=Pr(𝑧2)Pr(z2∣z3)=Pr(z2) if 𝑧2z2 and 𝑧3z3 are independent.


VII. Interpreting and factoring

The probability of an observation 𝑦y depends on a true ecological state of interest, 𝑧z, and the parameters in a data model, 𝜽𝑑θd. The probability of the true state 𝑧z depends on the parameters in an ecological process model, 𝜽𝑝θp. We know that 𝜽𝑑θd and 𝜽𝑝θp are independent. Write out a factored expression for the joint distribution, Pr(𝑦,𝑧,𝜽𝑑,𝜽𝑝)Pr(y,z,θd,θp). Drawing a Bayesian network will help.

Pr(𝑦,𝑧,𝜽𝑑,𝜽𝑝)=Pr(𝑦∣𝑧,𝜽𝑑)Pr(𝑧∣𝜽𝑝)Pr(𝜃𝑑)Pr(𝜽𝑝)Pr(y,z,θd,θp)=Pr(y∣z,θd)Pr(z∣θp)Pr(θd)Pr(θp)
